<div class="prose">

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">📌 Why these words?</div>
  <p>This unit closes the year. You will design a 2050 net-zero energy mix for a city and write a public-audience Op-Ed defending it. You will also write a Year-End Synthesis reflecting on all four course threads. The vocabulary below is the working language of energy systems and public-facing climate writing.</p>
</div>

<h2>Vocabulary</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Term</th>
      <th>What it means + visual cue</th>
      <th>Sentence stem</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Renewable</strong></td>
      <td>Energy from sources that naturally replenish — solar, wind, hydro, geothermal, biomass. <em>Visual: Sun, wind turbine, dam, geothermal vent.</em></td>
      <td>Renewable sources in my mix include ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Intermittency</strong></td>
      <td>Variation in output — solar at night = zero, wind on a calm day = zero. The main technical challenge for renewables. <em>Visual: Up-down sawtooth graph of solar output over a day.</em></td>
      <td>Intermittency in my mix is managed by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Baseload</strong></td>
      <td>The minimum power demand a grid must always meet. Historically supplied by coal, gas, or nuclear. <em>Visual: Flat-line graph at the bottom of a daily demand curve.</em></td>
      <td>Baseload in my plan is supplied by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Capacity factor</strong></td>
      <td>The fraction of nameplate capacity a power source actually delivers over time. Solar ~20-30%, nuclear ~90%, gas ~50%. <em>Visual: Bar showing "rated" vs. "actual" for different sources.</em></td>
      <td>The capacity factor of ___ in this region is about ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>LCOE</strong></td>
      <td>Levelized Cost of Energy — total lifetime cost divided by total energy produced. Standard way to compare sources. <em>Visual: Calculator with cost-per-kWh result.</em></td>
      <td>LCOE for ___ is approximately $___ per MWh.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Grid</strong></td>
      <td>The network that transmits and distributes electricity from generators to users. Modernizing the grid is part of every transition. <em>Visual: Web of power lines connecting plants and cities.</em></td>
      <td>Grid upgrades needed for this plan include ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Transmission</strong></td>
      <td>Moving electricity over long distances at high voltage. Key bottleneck for connecting renewables to demand centers. <em>Visual: High-voltage tower with long lines stretching to distant city.</em></td>
      <td>Transmission constraints in this region mean ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Net-zero</strong></td>
      <td>When greenhouse gas emissions are balanced by removals — emit some, remove the equivalent. The 2050 target for most national plans. <em>Visual: Balance scale with emissions on one side, removals on the other.</em></td>
      <td>Net-zero for this city by 2050 requires ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Just transition</strong></td>
      <td>Shifting away from fossil fuels in a way that protects workers, communities, and equity. Without a just transition, decarbonization fails politically. <em>Visual: Coal worker being trained in solar installation.</em></td>
      <td>A just transition in this city means ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Energy mix</strong></td>
      <td>The combination of sources providing a region's energy. Mixes are designed, not natural — you can change yours. <em>Visual: Pie chart with slices for each source.</em></td>
      <td>My proposed 2050 energy mix is ___% solar, ___% wind, ___% ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Lifecycle</strong></td>
      <td>The full environmental impact of a technology from materials extraction → manufacturing → operation → disposal. Honest comparison requires lifecycle thinking. <em>Visual: Circular arrow showing mining → manufacture → use → end-of-life.</em></td>
      <td>On a lifecycle basis, this source ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>EROI</strong></td>
      <td>Energy Return On Investment — energy you get out divided by energy you put in. Below 1, the source is a net consumer. <em>Visual: Equation: Energy Out / Energy In.</em></td>
      <td>EROI for ___ is approximately ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Decarbonization</strong></td>
      <td>Reducing the carbon intensity of an economy — replacing fossil fuels, electrifying transport, reducing material emissions. <em>Visual: Downward arrow on a CO₂-per-GDP graph.</em></td>
      <td>Decarbonization in this city must address ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Externality</strong></td>
      <td>A cost or benefit of a transaction borne by people not party to it. Fossil fuel pollution is a classic negative externality. <em>Visual: Factory smokestack with smoke drifting over a neighborhood.</em></td>
      <td>An externality of the current energy mix is ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Op-Ed</strong></td>
      <td>An opinion essay written for a public audience (usually 600-900 words). Argues a clear stance with evidence accessible to non-experts. <em>Visual: Newspaper opinion page with byline.</em></td>
      <td>My op-ed argues that ___ for the audience of ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Public audience</strong></td>
      <td>Readers who are not specialists. Requires plain language, vivid examples, and stakes that feel personal. Different from a policy brief or research paper. <em>Visual: Crowd of diverse readers looking at a newspaper.</em></td>
      <td>For a public audience, I will explain ___ by ___.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td><strong>Synthesis</strong></td>
      <td>Bringing multiple ideas together into a coherent whole. The Year-End Synthesis asks you to weave together the 4 course threads. <em>Visual: Multiple threads woven into a single rope.</em></td>
      <td>My synthesis ties together ___, ___, and ___.</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">🛠️ In-class pre-teach activity (10 min)</div>
  <p><strong>Mix sketch.</strong> Pick one of the 8 U7 city options. Sketch a proposed 2050 energy mix as a pie chart with labeled percentages. Annotate at least 5 terms from this list explaining your choices.</p>
</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">💬 Paired discussion prompt</div>
  <p>With a partner: each of you reads aloud the first sentence of an Op-Ed you would write. Critique each other's hook: does it grab a public audience? Does it use precise vocabulary or vague language? Revise together.</p>
</div>

